1":"1503–1571","1473–Female":"1473–Deceased","1503":"1503","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1473":"1473","1571":"1571","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","England":"England","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Glasgow, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thompson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>T(h)om(me)</i> (see   Thom  ) + <i>-son</i> ‘son of <i>Tom</i>’.   Thomson   is usually the Scottish form, that with the intrusive <i>-p-</i> being English. Both forms are common in Ireland. The surname <i>Thompson</i> is also very common among African Americans.","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Thomsen   and of its Swedish cognate <b>Thomsson</b>. Compare   Thomson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thomson","meanings":["Scottish, English and northern Irish: variant of   Thompson  .","Scottish: sometimes an Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>McThomas</i>; see   McTavish  ,   McComish  .","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Thomsen  . Compare   Thompson  ."]},{"name":"Thom","meanings":["Scottish and English: from the Middle English personal name <i>T(h)om(me)</i>, a pet form of   Thomas  . In Scotland, <i>Thom</i> is also an Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac Thom</i>, see   McComb  .","German: from the personal name <i>Thom</i>, a pet form of   Thomas  . This surname is also found in France.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 譚, see   Tan   1."]},{"name":"Tomson","meanings":["English: variant of   Thompson  ."]},{"name":"Thompsom","meanings":["Altered form of   Thompson  ."]},{"name":"Tompson","meanings":["English: variant of   Thompson  ."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":76,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":85,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":96,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705206,"age":98,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organiz